Here's a Java solution that uses bitwise operations to check if a number is a power of three without loops or recursion.

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // If n is less than 1, it's not a power of three
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }

        // If n is 1, it's a power of three
        if (n == 1) {
            return true;
        }

        // Use bitwise shift to check if n is a power of three
        while (n != 0) {
            // If n is not a power of three, it must have been shifted by 1
            if (n & 1 != 0) {
                return false;
            }
            // Shift n to the right by 1 bit
            n >>= 1;
        }

        // If n is a power of three, it must be 1
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

This solution works by shifting the bits of `n` to the right until only one bit is left. If `n` is not a power of three, this process must have shifted one bit to the right, so the function returns `false`. If `n` is a power of three, it must be 1, so the function returns `true`.

Here's an example use case:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Solution solution = new Solution();
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(27));  // true
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(0));   // false
        System.out.println(solution.isPowerOfThree(-1));  // false
    }
}
```

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n) because it uses bitwise shift operations, which are very efficient for large numbers. The space complexity is O(1) because it only uses a constant amount of space to store the variables.

